<section xml:id="theory-vs-law" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Theory vs. Law</title>

    <p> A <term>law</term> is a concise verbal or mathematical statement of a behavior or relation that always seems to be the same under the same conditions. A <term>theory</term> is a well-tested, unifying principle that explains a body of facts and the laws based on them. Essentially a law is the "what" and a theory is the "why". A few examples of laws include: Charles' Law, which is the relationship between temperature and pressure in gasses and the Law of Gravity. A few examples of theories include: Einstein's Theory of Relativity, Valence Bond Theory, and Kinetic Molecular Theory. Let's compare a few laws and theories to help better understand the difference between the two. </p>

